data.Name: Pad
data.Description: Onshore/land pad constructed for the purpose of drilling/completing wells and hosting other production related equipment.

data.Name: Pad (Single well)
data.Description: Onshore/land pad constructed for the purpose of drilling/completing one well.

data.Name: Pad (Multi-well)
data.Description: Onshore/land pad constructed for the purpose of drilling/completing multiple wells ranging from 2 wells to > 50 wells.

data.Name: Subsea Template
data.Description: An offshore structure located on the seabed designed to support drilling of and production from one or more wells tied back to a platform or floating production vessel. A template consists of slots for each well designed to support the wellhead and production manifolds.

data.Name: Subsea Well
data.Description: A location on the seabed from which a well is constructed. Surface hole sections may be drilled open to the seabed where water-based drilling fluids are used. Intermediate and production hole sections encountering higher pressure or drilled using non-water based drilling fluids will require a wellhead structure placed on the seabed tied to the conductor. The wellhead will be tied back to the rig via a subsea riser.

data.Name: Platform
data.Description: Large fixed or floating offshore structure with facilities to extract and process oil and natural gas that lie in geologic formations located beneath the seabed. A platform can host a drilling rig or other types of work unit to enable wells to be constructed and maintained.

data.Name: Platform (Rigid Leg)
data.Description: Platform built on steel legs driven into the seabed developed for very long term use.

data.Name: Platform (Tension Leg)
data.Description: TLPs are floating platforms tethered to the seabed in a manner that eliminates most vertical movement of the structure.

data.Name: Platform (Spar)
data.Description: A floating platform alternative that can support drilling, production and storage operations, the spar consists of a large vertical cylinder bearing topsides with equipment. Similar to an iceberg, the majority of a spar facility is located beneath the water's surface, providing the facility increased stability. There are three types of spars - classic single cylindrical hull, truss with shorter cylindrical hull supported by a truss fixed to the seabed and cell with multiple cylindrical hulls. Cylinders are either buoyancy only, or subdivided into buoyancy and ballast.

data.Name: Platform (Gravity Base)
data.Description: A gravity-based structure (GBS) of steel and concrete is a facility held in place on the seabed by gravity. Steel only GBS typically do not support liquid storage. Concrete GBS are often designed to include subsurface storage tanks.

data.Name: Platform (Compliant Tower)
data.Description: Compliant tower platforms consist of slender, flexible towers and a pile foundation supporting a conventional deck for drilling and production operations.

data.Name: Artificial Island
data.Description: A permanent or temporary artificial island constructed  to form a pad located above sea level. In arctic offshore areas, an artifical island is preferred over traditional platform types to provide protection from drifting pack ice.

data.Name: Artificial Island (Revetment)
data.Description: A permanent artificial island constructed by depositing rocks/gravel/sand/sand bags within a Revetment on the seabed to form a pad located above sea level. In arctic offshore areas, an artifical island is preferred over traditional platform types to provide protection from drifting pack ice.

data.Name: Artificial Island (Caisson)
data.Description: A permanent artificial island constructed from installation of a steel or concrete caisson backfilled with sand/gravel to form a pad located above sea level.  In arctic offshore areas, an artifical island is preferred over traditional platform types to provide protection from drifting pack ice.

data.Name: Artificial Island (Ice)
data.Description: A temporary artificial island constructed for exploration well drilling by spraying sea water into the air to form ice, gradually building up a large platform area that eventually grounds on the seabed.
